// Response 201

{

  "scim": {

    "enabled": true,

    "base_url": "https://api.foundry-iam.com/scim/v2/wsp_c91b12",

    "bearer_token": "scim_live_a1b2c3d4e5f6...",  // SHOWN ONCE — store immediately

    "token_prefix": "scim_liv",

    "schemas_url": "https://api.foundry-iam.com/scim/v2/wsp_c91b12/Schemas",

    "service_provider_config_url": "https://api.foundry-iam.com/scim/v2/wsp_c91b12/ServiceProviderConfig"

  },

  "warning": "The bearer_token will not be shown again. Copy it now."

}

5.2 PATCH /v1/workspaces/:id/scim/config

// Request

{

  "deprovision_action": "disable",

  "sync_groups": true,

  "allowed_operations": ["CREATE", "UPDATE", "DISABLE"],

  "user_attribute_mappings": {

    "urn:ietf:params:scim:schemas:extension:enterprise:2.0:User:employeeNumber": "attributes.employeeId"

  }

}



SECTION 6

SCIM Gateway — Implementation Details



6.1 Authentication Middleware

All SCIM requests must carry a workspace-scoped Bearer token. The SCIM Gateway validates the token on every request.

// SCIM auth middleware pseudocode

async function scimAuth(req, res, next) {

  const workspaceId = req.params.workspaceId;

  const token = extractBearer(req.headers.authorization);

  if (!token) return res.status(401).json(scimError('Unauthorized', 401));

  const tokenHash = sha256(token);

  const config = await db.scim_configurations.findOne({

    workspace_id: workspaceId,

    bearer_token_hash: tokenHash,

    enabled: true

  });

  if (!config) return res.status(401).json(scimError('Unauthorized', 401));

  req.scimConfig = config;

  req.workspaceId = workspaceId;

  next();

}

6.2 ServiceProviderConfig Response

The /ServiceProviderConfig endpoint tells the IdP what SCIM operations Foundry IAM supports. This is critical — IdPs (Okta, Azure AD) read this before configuring the integration.

{

  "schemas": ["urn:ietf:params:scim:schemas:core:2.0:ServiceProviderConfig"],

  "documentationUri": "https://docs.foundry-iam.com/scim",

  "patch": { "supported": true },

  "bulk": { "supported": false, "maxOperations": 0, "maxPayloadSize": 0 },

  "filter": { "supported": true, "maxResults": 200 },

  "changePassword": { "supported": false },

  "sort": { "supported": false },

  "etag": { "supported": false },

  "authenticationSchemes": [{

    "type": "oauthbearertoken",

    "name": "OAuth Bearer Token",

    "description": "Authentication scheme using OAuth2 Bearer Token"

  }]

}

6.3 Error Response Format (SCIM standard)

SCIM has its own error response format (RFC 7644 §3.12). Do NOT use the control plane error format for SCIM endpoints.

{

  "schemas": ["urn:ietf:params:scim:api:messages:2.0:Error"],

  "status": "400",

  "scimType": "invalidValue",

  "detail": "userName is required"

}

6.4 Pagination

SCIM uses startIndex + count pagination (1-based index). All list endpoints must implement this.

// GET /scim/v2/{workspace_id}/Users?startIndex=1&count=100

{

  "schemas": ["urn:ietf:params:scim:api:messages:2.0:ListResponse"],

  "totalResults": 350,

  "startIndex": 1,

  "itemsPerPage": 100,

  "Resources": [ /* array of User objects */ ]

}

6.5 Filtering

IdPs use SCIM filter queries to check if users already exist before creating them. Foundry IAM must support the minimum required filter operators.

Filter Example

When Used

filter=userName eq "jane@acme.com"

Check if user exists by username — required for all IdPs

filter=externalId eq "okta-abc-123"

Check by external ID — required for Okta

filter=emails.value eq "jane@acme.com"

Check by email — required for Azure AD



